Q1.1: K-Means Clustering of Movie Reviews¶

In this Section, cluster the 956 movie reviews collected from homework 05 with the KMeans clustering algorithm.

This algorithm is a centroid-based clustering model to cluster data into groups or clusters of equal variances.

The number of clusters (k) should be specified in advance. Here, we compare the clustering results with k=4 and k=8.

## normalize_corpus function to normalize corpus
def normalize_corpus(corpus, lemmatize=True, only_text_chars=False, tokenize=False):
    
    normalized_corpus = []
    html_parser = HTMLParser()
    
    for text in corpus:
        text = html_parser.unescape(text)        
        text = expand_contractions(text, CONTRACTION_MAP)
        
        if lemmatize:
            text = lemmatize_text(text)
        else:
            text = text.lower()
        text = remove_special_characters(text)
        text = remove_stopwords(text)
        
        if only_text_chars:
            text = keep_text_characters(text)
        
        if tokenize:
            text = tokenize_text(text)
            normalized_corpus.append(text)
        else:
            normalized_corpus.append(text)
            
    return normalized_corpus
In [6]:
## expand_contractions function to expand contractions
def expand_contractions(text, contraction_mapping):
    contractions_pattern = re.compile('({})'.format('|'.join(contraction_mapping.keys())),
                                      flags=re.IGNORECASE|re.DOTALL)
    def expand_match(contraction):
        match = contraction.group(0)
        first_char = match[0]
        expanded_contraction = contraction_mapping.get(match)\
                               if contraction_mapping.get(match)\
                               else contraction_mapping.get(match.lower())
        expanded_contraction = first_char+expanded_contraction[1:]
        return expanded_contraction
        
    expanded_text = contractions_pattern.sub(expand_match, text)
    expanded_text = re.sub("'", "", expanded_text)
    return expanded_text
In [7]:
## remove_special_characters function to remove special characters
def remove_special_characters(text):
    tokens = tokenize_text(text)
    pattern = re.compile('[{}]'.format(re.escape(string.punctuation)))
    filtered_tokens = filter(None, [pattern.sub(' ', token) for token in tokens])
    filtered_text = ' '.join(filtered_tokens)
    return filtered_text
In [8]:
## tokenize_text function for tokenization
def tokenize_text(text):
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
    tokens = [token.strip() for token in tokens]
    return tokens
In [9]:
## remove_stopwords function to remove stop words
def remove_stopwords(text):
    tokens = tokenize_text(text)
    stopword_list = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')
    filtered_tokens = [token for token in tokens if token not in stopword_list]
    filtered_text = ' '.join(filtered_tokens)    
    return filtered_text

## Function for getting root words by lemmetization of the tokens
def lemming(tokens, pos = 'n'):
    
    lemma = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemmad_list =[]
    
    for i in tokens:
        List =list(nltk.pos_tag([i])[0])[1]
        if(List in ['NNPS','NNS', 'NN']):
            pos = 'n' ## noun
        if(List in ['JJS','JJR']): 
            pos ='a' ## adjective
        if(List in ['RB','RBS','RBR','MB', 'VBN', 'VBD', 'VBG']): 
            pos ='v' ## verb and adverbs
        lemmad_list= lemmad_list+ [lemma.lemmatize(i, pos)]
    return lemmad_list
In [12]:
## function for tokenizing the text and getting root words by lemmetization of the tokens
def Tokenize_text(text):
    RT = nltk.RegexpTokenizer(pattern=r'\s+',gaps =True)
    tokens = RT.tokenize(text)
    Tokens =lemming(tokens)
    return Tokens

In [16]:
## get key features for each cluster and get reviews belonging to each other
for cluster_num_4 in range(NUM_CLUSTERS_4):
    key_features_4 = [feature_names_4[index] for index in ordered_centroids_4[cluster_num_4, :topn_features]]
    rAuthor_4 = movie_clusters_4[movie_clusters_4['kmeans_cluster'] == cluster_num_4]['rAuthor'].values.tolist()
    print('CLUSTER #' + str(cluster_num_4+1))
    print('Key Features:', key_features_4)
    print('Popular Review Authors:', rAuthor_4)
    print('-'*80)

## create data frame that has the result of the MDS plus the cluster numbers and titles
df_k4 = pd.DataFrame(dict(x=xs4, y=ys4, label=clusters_4, title=scale_4)) 

## group by cluster
groups = df_k4.groupby('label')

## set up plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10)) # set size
ax.margins(0.05) # Optional, just adds 5% padding to the autoscaling

## iterate through groups to layer the plot
## note that I use the cluster_name and cluster_color dicts with the 'name' lookup to return the appropriate color/label
for name, group in groups:    
    ax.plot(group.x, 
            group.y, 
            marker='o', linestyle='', 
            markersize=12,             
            label=cluster_names_4[name], 
            color=cluster_colors_4[name], 
            mec='none')
        
    # ax.set_aspect('auto')
    ax.set_aspect('equal')
    ax.tick_params(\
        axis= 'x',          # changes apply to the x-axis
        which='both',      # both major and minor ticks are affected
        bottom='False',      # ticks along the bottom edge are off
        top='False',         # ticks along the top edge are off
        labelbottom='False')
    
    ax.tick_params(\
        axis= 'y',         # changes apply to the y-axis
        which='both',      # both major and minor ticks are affected
        left='False',      # ticks along the bottom edge are off
        top='False',         # ticks along the top edge are off
        labelleft='False')
    
ax.legend(numpoints=1)  #show legend with only 1 point

#add label in x,y position with the label as the film title
for i in range(len(df_k4)):
    ax.text(df_k4.ix[i]['x'], df_k4.ix[i]['y'], int(df_k4.ix[i]['title']), size=12)    
        
## plt.show()

plt.savefig('km4_cluster.png', dpi=300)

## function for Ward's agglomerative hierarchical clustering
def ward_hierarchical_clustering(cv_matrix):
    cosine_distance = 1 - cosine_similarity(cv_matrix)
    linkage_matrix = ward(cosine_distance)
    return linkage_matrix

## function for plotting hierarchical clusters
def plot_hierarchical_clusters(linkage_matrix, MoviesReviews, p=100, figure_size=(8,12)):
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figure_size)
    movie_titles = MoviesReviews['rAuthor'].values.tolist()
    
    R = dendrogram(linkage_matrix, orientation="left", labels=movie_titles, truncate_mode='lastp', p=p, no_plot=True)
    temp = {R["leaves"][ii]:MoviesReviews.rTitle[ii] for ii in range(len(R["leaves"]))}
    
    def llf(xx):
        return "{}".format(temp[xx])
    
    ax = dendrogram(linkage_matrix, 
                    orientation="left", 
                    labels=movie_titles, 
                    truncate_mode='lastp', 
                    p=p,
                    leaf_label_func = llf,
                    leaf_font_size=10)
    
    plt.tick_params(axis= 'x',
                    which='both',
                    bottom='False',
                    top='False',
                    labelbottom='False')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig('hc_clusters.png', dpi=300)

Q2.1 The KMeans algorithm¶

The KMeans algorithm clusters data by trying to separate samples in n groups of equal variances, minimizing a criterion known as the inertia (within-cluster sum-of-squares) which can be recognized as a measure of how internally coherent clusters are. This algorithm requires the number of clusters to be specified.

'inertia' is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.

The Silhouette coefficient is calculated using the mean intra-cluster distance (a) and the mean nearest-cluster distance (b) for each sample. The Silhouette Coefficient for a sample is (b - a) / max(a, b). The best value is 1 and the worst value is -1. Values near 0 indicate overlapping clusters. Negative values generally indicate that a sample has been assigned to the wrong cluster, as a different cluster is more similar.

In this homework, the inertia and silhouette Coefficient are used to compare the models with n_clusters 4 and 8. The results indicate the KMeans clustering algorithm performs better when n_clusters (k) = 4 (silhouette coefficient = 0.19).

Q2.2 The Hierarchical clustering algorithm¶

Hierarchical clustering, as depicted by a tree or dendrogram, can be divided into agglomerative ("from the bottom up") and divisive clustering ("from the top down").

There are four linkages (complete, average, ward and single) linkage for hierarchical agglomerative clustering with the basic idea to repeatedly merge two most similar groups as measured by the linkage. Complete linkage measures the farthest pair of points, average linkage measures the average dissimilarity over all pairs, ward linkage measures how much the sum of squares will increase when we merge two clusters, and single linkage measures the closest pair of points.

In this homework, the hierarchical clustering algorithm (linkage 'ward', and n_clusters = 4) performs better (silhouette coefficient = 0.45).

In [41]:

Q3.3 - Compare Silhouette Coefficient in Clustering Models¶

The silhouette coefficient is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster compared to other clusters. The silhouette ranges from 1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. The silhouette coefficients can be calculated with any distance metric

From the silhouette coefficient results in 4 clustering models, the hierarchical clustering algorithm (linkage 'ward', and n_clusters = 4) performs best (silhouette coefficient = 0.45).
